Package ch.nolix.nolixCommonLibrary.interfaces

  • Interface Summary 
    Interface Description
    Activable
    An activable object is an object that can be activated or inactivated.
    Classable
    A classable object is an object that can have a class.
    Classed
    A classed object is an object that has a class.
    Clearable
    A clearable object is an object that can be empty.
    Configurable
    A configurable object is a specifiable object that probably has a name or class and that contains other configurable objects.
    DeterminedIndexed
    A determined indexed object is an object that has a determined index.
    DeterminedNamed
    A final named object is an object that has a determined name.
    DeterminedSIMPLE_CLASS_NAMEd
    A final SIMPLE_CLASS_NAMEd object is an object that has a determined SIMPLE_CLASS_NAME.
    DeterminedVersioned
    A final version object is an object that has a determined single version number.
    IContainerOfNamables
    A container of namables is a container that contains namable objects.
    IContainerOfNameds
    A container of namables is a container that contains named objects.
    IErrorReporter
    An error reporter is an object that can display internally occurring errors.
    IReceiver
    A receiver is an object that can receive messages.
    Mockable
    A mockable object is an object that normally runs like as a regular instance and that can be once set to be a mock.
    Namable
    A namable element is an object that can have a name.
    Named
    A named object is an object that has a name.
    Resettable
    A resettable object is an object that can be reseted.
    Signable
    A signable object is an object that can have an info string.
    Signed
    A signed object is an object that has an info string.
    Specifiable
    A specifiable object is a determined SIMPLE_CLASS_NAMEd object attributes can be set to or removed from.
    Stoppable
    A stoppable object is an object that can be stopped.
